        "output": `<img src="./assets/visual_outputs/bajade.png" alt="">`,
        "explanation": " LEDs turn light into numbers, beauty summoned from code. It reflects the paradox of our age: science and technology create stunning art, yet they also reduce life to data. Our endless thoughts, expressions, memories, and creations become streams of digits. Consciousness rendered discrete, compressed, and categorized. This generator is a microcosm of that tension: it is creative and reductive at the same time, a device capable of wonder that nonetheless translates everything into integers and voltages. Somewhere in some database, we’re all just collections of values waiting to be parsed, predicted, and profited from by advertisers and businesses. <br> And layered beneath this lies the strangeness of being human. Our senses take in the world continuously. Light, sound, touch flowing in gradients too rich to quantify—but what we perceive is endlessly subjective. We live in private perceptual universes, stitched together from neural interpretations. Case in point: do we even see the same colors? Is your red the same as mine, or is it simply a shared linguistic truce masking wildly different inner experiences? Technology can measure wavelengths with perfect precision, but it can’t tell us what crimson feels like to someone else. <br> So we navigate this contradiction: machines that discretize everything, and minds that swim in subjectivity, systems that demand quantification, and senses that resist it. In this contrast between the measurable and the immeasurable modern life unfolds, flickering like LEDs translating the infinite spectrum of human experience into the narrow, numerical language of code. <br><br> <a href='https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1fFLlyW3LKELSG2XC9wQoCUlBf25IFjbz?usp=sharing'>Download Link</a>",
