        "explanation": `Beyond the Frame of Time is a mixed-media art piece that combines painting and sculpture. It features an Aurora, a natural wonder, alongside an emerging human form that represents humanity's understanding of nature and life itself, which has led to the development of Science, Technology, and Society. The piece honors both creative marvel and scientific mastery,  showing how each illuminates the other.<br><br> <span class="indent">The</span> Aurora lights signify that natural life, at its core, is the root of all existence. This forms the foundation of the vast scientific knowledge mankind possesses. From the littlest organism to the horizon of the universe, there is more of the unknown than what humanity has discovered.  Science strives to decipher and comprehend so that the power of the human mind can emerge and form new, profound knowledge. The beauty of existence becomes no longer a mystery with scientific methods, transforming wonders into data that develops technology and shapes societies. This translates potential into reality, embodied in the emerging DNA helices. Yet, over time, excessive and unnecessary disturbance to nature has consequences. The rippled waters distort the reflection of the aurora, symbolizing the adverse effects of science and technology, such as environmental damage and social issues, including defiance of human ethics, for instance, unethical experimentations.  This sends a message that science is to humanely develop technology and society, not to exploit and play god.<br><br><span class="indent">At</span> a conceptual level, the artwork reflects the evolution of human knowledge— from observing natural beauty to deciphering its laws, creating new realities, and shaping better futures. The piece links together the power of the human mind, the evolution of life, the development of science and technology, the impacts on life sustainability, and, overall, ethical boundaries— how far should humans go in manipulating life? At what point do human creations stop honoring nature and begin to defy it?`,
