        "output": `<img src="./assets/visual_outputs/bertiz.jpg" alt="Upcycling the Fragments of Future by Ashley Grace Bertiz">`,
        "explanation": `Upcycling the Fragments of Future is an Eco-Art Mixed Media work that highlights the importance of sustainability for a better world. It depicts as well the upbringings of waste coming from scientific and technological innovations, which led to its exponential growth in this planet, affecting the environment.<br><br>In a literal sense, the artwork contains elements such as non-biodegradable waste like plastics, unused materials like old clothes, and natural elements like leaves and flowers. Wastes are then repurposed into a work of art. It aligns to the concept of Eco-Art, and the artwork shows how such materials related to environmental science can be converted into an art form that upholds sustainability, creativity, and functionality.<br><br>In a figurative sense, it shows how unsustainable practices regarding waste have led to environmental degradation. How did waste even manage to grow that many? One factor here is the growing scientific and technological innovation, which then led to higher production and higher compilation of wastes (which is seen at the compilation of trash below the artwork). The center piece, the flowers that are now withered, depicts the degradation of the environment. It shows how scientific innovations, while beneficial, have its flaws, such as affecting the environment in the long run.<br><br>All in all, the art piece shows how important it is to look at the critical lens, on how scientific innovations also had its repercussions, especially in the environment. Now, as a collective, we must truly uphold dealing with environmental issues. One solution among many is turning wastes into a functional use, and an example for that is the artwork that I made. It is important that now, to achieve sustainability, we must start upcycling the fragments that could affect our future, in order to grant us the chance to upcycle the fragments of an ideal future.`,
